      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the confusion! Let's get straight to the point. The Circle of Fifths is a visual representation of the relationships among the 12 tones of the chromatic scale, their corresponding key signatures, and the associated major and minor keys.\n\nHere's the pattern of sharps and flats as you move around the circle:\n\n1. Start at C major, which has no sharps or flats.\n2. Move clockwise to G major, which adds F♯ (one sharp).\n3. Next is D major, adding C♯ (two sharps).\n4. Then E major, with G♯ (three sharps).\n5. F♯ major, which has four sharps (F♯, C♯, G♯, D♯).\n6. B major, adding A♯ (five sharps).\n7. E♭ major, with six sharps (F♯, C♯, G♯, D♯, A♯, B♭).\n8. A major, seven sharps (F♯, C♯, G♯, D♯, A♯, B♭, E♭).\n9. D♭ major,",
